WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.343 --> 00:00:03.426
(gentle intro music)

2
00:00:08.280 --> 00:00:12.390
<v ->Okay so, last pulmonary talk, Pulmonary Potpourri,</v>

3
00:00:12.390 --> 00:00:14.130
there's a lot of things we're gonna discuss here.

4
00:00:14.130 --> 00:00:15.680
Let's go ahead and get started.

5
00:00:17.340 --> 00:00:19.040
Okay, let's start with a question.

6
00:00:20.460 --> 00:00:24.240
This is our same COPD patient from this morning.

7
00:00:24.240 --> 00:00:26.880
So, this is our 52-year-old patient with COPD,

8
00:00:26.880 --> 00:00:30.030
and a 20 pack-year smoking history.

9
00:00:30.030 --> 00:00:32.430
They come in for a comprehensive well visit.

10
00:00:32.430 --> 00:00:34.680
They have successfully quit smoking last year,

11
00:00:34.680 --> 00:00:36.180
after your recommendation,

12
00:00:36.180 --> 00:00:37.860
good job,

13
00:00:37.860 --> 00:00:40.950
and they are otherwise stable, with no other comorbidities.

14
00:00:40.950 --> 00:00:43.350
Which one of the following screening tests for lung cancer

15
00:00:43.350 --> 00:00:44.790
is currently recommended

16
00:00:44.790 --> 00:00:48.210
by the U.S. Preventive Services Task Force?

17
00:00:48.210 --> 00:00:49.950
Please pay very careful attention

18
00:00:49.950 --> 00:00:53.160
to all these Task Force recommendations.

19
00:00:53.160 --> 00:00:55.440
Should we do A., a chest x-ray,

20
00:00:55.440 --> 00:00:59.640
B., a low-dose chest CT now,

21
00:00:59.640 --> 00:01:03.450
C., a low-dose chest CT at age 55,

22
00:01:03.450 --> 00:01:06.753
or D., no screening test is currently recommended?

23
00:01:07.710 --> 00:01:09.930
What do we like in our 52-year-old patient

24
00:01:09.930 --> 00:01:13.200
with a 20 pack-year smoking history?

25
00:01:13.200 --> 00:01:15.810
We all know what a pack-year is, right?

26
00:01:15.810 --> 00:01:18.810
It's the equivalent of smoking a pack a day for a year.

27
00:01:18.810 --> 00:01:21.510
So if you smoked two packs a day for 10 years,

28
00:01:21.510 --> 00:01:23.360
that would be a 20 pack-year history.

29
00:01:28.800 --> 00:01:29.633
Okay, good.

30
00:01:29.633 --> 00:01:31.170
The majority of you got the correct answer,

31
00:01:31.170 --> 00:01:33.660
the second highest plurality

32
00:01:33.660 --> 00:01:35.640
was the previous recommendation,

33
00:01:35.640 --> 00:01:39.300
so you were on the right track, just you weren't updated.

34
00:01:39.300 --> 00:01:41.430
So, let's get into it.

35
00:01:41.430 --> 00:01:42.270
Lung cancer screening.

36
00:01:42.270 --> 00:01:46.140
So, lung cancer is the number one cause

37
00:01:46.140 --> 00:01:48.520
of cancer-related deaths in men and women

38
00:01:50.400 --> 00:01:51.423
above the age of 50.

39
00:01:53.820 --> 00:01:55.800
The death rate is increasing,

40
00:01:55.800 --> 00:01:58.890
the five-year survival rate is unfortunately high,

41
00:01:58.890 --> 00:02:03.300
and 95% of those at risk are not being screened.

42
00:02:03.300 --> 00:02:05.430
How many of us are doing lung cancer screening

43
00:02:05.430 --> 00:02:07.380
in our practices?

44
00:02:07.380 --> 00:02:09.090
Good, it needs to be everyone,

45
00:02:09.090 --> 00:02:11.550
if you're doing outpatient medicine.

46
00:02:11.550 --> 00:02:14.430
Here's the mortality rates of lung cancer,

47
00:02:14.430 --> 00:02:18.603
which bests prostate, breast, and pancreas deaths combined.

48
00:02:20.790 --> 00:02:22.350
Now, David showed a lot of these maps,

49
00:02:22.350 --> 00:02:24.300
I think they're fun too.

50
00:02:24.300 --> 00:02:27.720
This is the lung cancer case rates in the United States.

51
00:02:27.720 --> 00:02:30.120
Definitely the Appalachia, down through the deep south,

52
00:02:30.120 --> 00:02:32.730
is problematic with lung cancer.

53
00:02:32.730 --> 00:02:35.880
And then the next one is lung cancer death rates.

54
00:02:35.880 --> 00:02:38.430
So, it's interesting, you know?

55
00:02:38.430 --> 00:02:42.750
What is happening down through Appalachia and in the south?

56
00:02:42.750 --> 00:02:44.553
Is it socioeconomic?

57
00:02:46.140 --> 00:02:48.420
Is it access to care?

58
00:02:48.420 --> 00:02:49.253
Education?

59
00:02:49.253 --> 00:02:51.180
There's so many ways we could look at this,

60
00:02:51.180 --> 00:02:52.480
but it's very interesting.

61
00:02:54.870 --> 00:02:56.880
Okay, our risks of lung cancer,

62
00:02:56.880 --> 00:02:58.920
smoking is the number one risk factor in this country,

63
00:02:58.920 --> 00:03:00.453
makes up for over 80% of causes,

64
00:03:00.453 --> 00:03:03.540
this could be primary or secondary.

65
00:03:03.540 --> 00:03:04.680
Cigars can be dangerous,

66
00:03:04.680 --> 00:03:06.300
but they don't tend to do as many.

67
00:03:06.300 --> 00:03:08.700
How many of us know what a hookah is?

68
00:03:08.700 --> 00:03:09.750
Hookah?

69
00:03:09.750 --> 00:03:11.610
Yeah, these are really becoming popular with young people.

70
00:03:11.610 --> 00:03:13.080
I live in Detroit,

71
00:03:13.080 --> 00:03:16.860
and Metro Detroit is the second largest Arab community

72
00:03:16.860 --> 00:03:17.940
outside the Middle East,

73
00:03:17.940 --> 00:03:19.350
so my best friend is Arab,

74
00:03:19.350 --> 00:03:21.450
like, hookahs are everywhere,

75
00:03:21.450 --> 00:03:23.730
and they're extremely dangerous,

76
00:03:23.730 --> 00:03:25.290
but they don't think that they are,

77
00:03:25.290 --> 00:03:30.290
because they filter the tobacco through water,

78
00:03:30.360 --> 00:03:32.550
and it's cooled, and flavored,

79
00:03:32.550 --> 00:03:33.750
and they think it's fun.

80
00:03:34.800 --> 00:03:36.360
Vaping, we don't know the risks.

81
00:03:36.360 --> 00:03:38.790
You know, as I mentioned earlier today,

82
00:03:38.790 --> 00:03:41.610
the lungs are just not a good delivery system,

83
00:03:41.610 --> 00:03:43.710
the lungs are very sensitive to damage.

84
00:03:43.710 --> 00:03:45.270
So, have your nicotine,

85
00:03:45.270 --> 00:03:46.320
have at it,

86
00:03:46.320 --> 00:03:48.390
do the patch or the gum,

87
00:03:48.390 --> 00:03:50.460
but the vaping, and the smoking,

88
00:03:50.460 --> 00:03:52.830
and all these things are very dangerous to the lungs.

89
00:03:52.830 --> 00:03:54.900
Don't forget about environmental toxins,

90
00:03:54.900 --> 00:03:57.480
like radon and air pollution,

91
00:03:57.480 --> 00:03:58.803
worse in other countries.

92
00:04:00.660 --> 00:04:03.000
Age, of course, is always a risk factor for lung cancer,

93
00:04:03.000 --> 00:04:04.530
as well as family history.

94
00:04:04.530 --> 00:04:05.970
The presentation, you all know this,

95
00:04:05.970 --> 00:04:08.880
cough, chest pain, dyspnea, hemoptysis.

96
00:04:08.880 --> 00:04:10.200
Clearly.

97
00:04:10.200 --> 00:04:13.620
Now, we divide lung cancer into small cell

98
00:04:13.620 --> 00:04:17.490
and non-small cell, histologically.

99
00:04:17.490 --> 00:04:21.330
So your small cell cancers make up the minority, 10 to 15%,

100
00:04:21.330 --> 00:04:25.140
they tend to occur in a central or mediastinal location,

101
00:04:25.140 --> 00:04:30.140
and there we see it in that left perihilar area.

102
00:04:31.950 --> 00:04:33.780
Unfortunately, they're very aggressive,

103
00:04:33.780 --> 00:04:35.460
and they metastasize early,

104
00:04:35.460 --> 00:04:39.570
and therefore they do confer a poorer prognosis.

105
00:04:39.570 --> 00:04:44.280
The only upside to a fast-growing tumor

106
00:04:44.280 --> 00:04:46.590
is that it is susceptible to chemotherapy,

107
00:04:46.590 --> 00:04:49.743
and that is therefore the primary treatment for small cells.

108
00:04:50.610 --> 00:04:52.410
Non-small cells make up 80%,

109
00:04:52.410 --> 00:04:54.450
the majority of these are adenose.

110
00:04:54.450 --> 00:04:56.130
They typically occur in the periphery,

111
00:04:56.130 --> 00:04:57.450
where you see the box,

112
00:04:57.450 --> 00:04:59.310
often in underlying lung disease.

113
00:04:59.310 --> 00:05:01.410
I mean, this patient looks emphysematous to me,

114
00:05:01.410 --> 00:05:03.360
based on that radiograph.

115
00:05:03.360 --> 00:05:04.590
They're slower growing,

116
00:05:04.590 --> 00:05:05.880
they have a better prognosis,

117
00:05:05.880 --> 00:05:08.793
and therefore surgical resection is the primary treatment.

118
00:05:10.830 --> 00:05:14.730
Now, this is the updated lung cancer screening guidelines

119
00:05:14.730 --> 00:05:16.650
from the U.S. Preventive Services Task Force.

120
00:05:16.650 --> 00:05:19.590
In 2021, they upped the guideline.

121
00:05:19.590 --> 00:05:23.340
It used to be age 55 with a 30 pack-year history, right?

122
00:05:23.340 --> 00:05:28.340
They've lowered it to age 50 with a 20 pack-year history,

123
00:05:28.980 --> 00:05:32.010
'cause they wanna pick up more and more of these cancers.

124
00:05:32.010 --> 00:05:33.570
So, that's a grade B recommendation,

125
00:05:33.570 --> 00:05:36.480
and I believe David mentioned this

126
00:05:36.480 --> 00:05:38.070
earlier in the presentation,

127
00:05:38.070 --> 00:05:39.930
or in the conference, rather,

128
00:05:39.930 --> 00:05:42.420
anytime the U.S. Preventive Services Task Force

129
00:05:42.420 --> 00:05:44.820
gives an A or a B recommendation,

130
00:05:44.820 --> 00:05:47.490
the insurance companies are forced by law to cover them,

131
00:05:47.490 --> 00:05:48.930
they can't say no.

132
00:05:48.930 --> 00:05:51.033
So, yes to lung cancer screening.

133
00:05:54.900 --> 00:05:59.900
Now, Medicare only pays for this up to age 75,

134
00:05:59.940 --> 00:06:02.790
because, you know, the average life expectancy is about 80,

135
00:06:02.790 --> 00:06:04.080
so they tend to cut it off,

136
00:06:04.080 --> 00:06:09.000
even though the Task Force recommends doing it up to 80,

137
00:06:09.000 --> 00:06:11.220
you probably won't get insurance companies to cover it

138
00:06:11.220 --> 00:06:13.383
after age 74.

139
00:06:14.850 --> 00:06:16.100
All right, next question.

140
00:06:18.480 --> 00:06:21.930
Which one of the following diseases is the most common cause

141
00:06:21.930 --> 00:06:25.650
of both secondary hypertension and resistant hypertension?

142
00:06:25.650 --> 00:06:28.410
Is it A., hyperthyroidism?

143
00:06:28.410 --> 00:06:31.230
Is it B., obstructive sleep apnea?

144
00:06:31.230 --> 00:06:33.870
Is it C., pheochromocytoma?

145
00:06:33.870 --> 00:06:36.720
Or D., renal artery stenosis?

146
00:06:36.720 --> 00:06:39.753
I was also asked this question on the boards last year.

147
00:06:44.760 --> 00:06:47.250
Great. Obstructive sleep apnea is the answer.

148
00:06:47.250 --> 00:06:51.490
So, sleep apnea is caused by a collapse

149
00:06:53.220 --> 00:06:54.870
in the soft tissues in the back of the throat.

150
00:06:54.870 --> 00:06:57.420
This occurs when the patient's sleeping,

151
00:06:57.420 --> 00:06:59.160
especially if they're laying on their back,

152
00:06:59.160 --> 00:07:01.050
that results in snoring,

153
00:07:01.050 --> 00:07:05.883
and can also go on to cause apnea and hypopneas.

154
00:07:07.020 --> 00:07:09.090
In the absence of cranial facial abnormalities,

155
00:07:09.090 --> 00:07:10.230
blah blah blah blah blah,

156
00:07:10.230 --> 00:07:13.560
you don't wanna step on any ENT's toes,

157
00:07:13.560 --> 00:07:17.520
generally speaking, everyone with sleep apnea snores,

158
00:07:17.520 --> 00:07:19.710
but not everyone who snores has sleep apnea.

159
00:07:19.710 --> 00:07:21.840
So the risk factors for OSA,

160
00:07:21.840 --> 00:07:23.940
I made it easy for you, OSA.

161
00:07:23.940 --> 00:07:26.250
Obesity, that's the most important risk,

162
00:07:26.250 --> 00:07:28.320
male sex, and age over 40.

163
00:07:28.320 --> 00:07:30.843
So, those are the hallmark risk factors.

164
00:07:31.830 --> 00:07:35.040
The consequences of this can be many,

165
00:07:35.040 --> 00:07:37.080
high blood pressure, as we mentioned,

166
00:07:37.080 --> 00:07:38.970
one of the leading causes of secondary,

167
00:07:38.970 --> 00:07:40.980
as well as resistant, hypertension,

168
00:07:40.980 --> 00:07:44.070
cardiovascular disease, sleep and memory problems,

169
00:07:44.070 --> 00:07:45.810
you know, daytime sleepiness,

170
00:07:45.810 --> 00:07:48.690
they could fall asleep at the wheel and crash their car.

171
00:07:48.690 --> 00:07:53.100
So, this is not just an obnoxious snoring problem.

172
00:07:53.100 --> 00:07:56.760
The symptoms are nocturnal or daytime.

173
00:07:56.760 --> 00:07:58.650
The hallmark are the three S's,

174
00:07:58.650 --> 00:08:03.210
that's snoring, excessive daytime sleepiness,

175
00:08:03.210 --> 00:08:05.403
and significant other complaints.

176
00:08:06.840 --> 00:08:08.670
The partner's like, "You gotta do something.

177
00:08:08.670 --> 00:08:11.877
He's like, stopping breathing when he's in his sleep."

178
00:08:13.560 --> 00:08:15.060
All right.

179
00:08:15.060 --> 00:08:16.559
How about questionnaires?

180
00:08:16.559 --> 00:08:19.080
Yes! The questionnaires, right?

181
00:08:19.080 --> 00:08:21.630
So, we're all gonna do these questionnaires in our office.

182
00:08:21.630 --> 00:08:24.510
My EHR likes the Epworth Sleepiness Scale,

183
00:08:24.510 --> 00:08:27.870
but the STOP-BANG Score actually has better data,

184
00:08:27.870 --> 00:08:30.810
because it has a lot of objective criteria,

185
00:08:30.810 --> 00:08:34.230
including, you know, age, BMI,

186
00:08:34.230 --> 00:08:36.993
neck circumference, gender, and blood pressure.

187
00:08:39.330 --> 00:08:40.170
How do you diagnose it?

188
00:08:40.170 --> 00:08:41.820
Well, you do a sleep study.

189
00:08:41.820 --> 00:08:44.250
If the patient is moderate risk,

190
00:08:44.250 --> 00:08:45.900
you can do a home-based sleep study.

191
00:08:45.900 --> 00:08:47.610
If they're higher risk,

192
00:08:47.610 --> 00:08:49.893
then you need the full polysomnography.

193
00:08:51.900 --> 00:08:54.240
Now, the test is looking for apneas,

194
00:08:54.240 --> 00:08:56.460
which is a lack of breathing for more than 10 seconds,

195
00:08:56.460 --> 00:08:58.350
or hypopnea, with the shallow breathing.

196
00:08:58.350 --> 00:08:59.730
They add these together,

197
00:08:59.730 --> 00:09:02.220
and you get the Apnea-Hypopnea Index,

198
00:09:02.220 --> 00:09:03.960
and this is the money slide.

199
00:09:03.960 --> 00:09:08.960
So AHI between 5 and 14 is mild sleep apnea,

200
00:09:09.000 --> 00:09:11.430
between 15 and 30 is moderate,

201
00:09:11.430 --> 00:09:13.650
greater than 30 is severe.

202
00:09:13.650 --> 00:09:15.630
Those numbers, we need to memorize,

203
00:09:15.630 --> 00:09:17.880
because they have implications for treatment.

204
00:09:19.860 --> 00:09:21.960
The task force in 2022 said

205
00:09:21.960 --> 00:09:25.530
there's inconclusive, insufficient evidence

206
00:09:25.530 --> 00:09:28.110
to assess screening for sleep apnea

207
00:09:28.110 --> 00:09:30.150
in an asymptomatic adult.

208
00:09:30.150 --> 00:09:31.627
So a patient comes in, and they say,

209
00:09:31.627 --> 00:09:33.960
"Oh, you know, I think I might have sleep apnea."

210
00:09:33.960 --> 00:09:35.467
And I'm like, "Well, do you snore?"

211
00:09:35.467 --> 00:09:36.427
"Yes."

212
00:09:36.427 --> 00:09:39.307
"Do you have excessive daytime sleepiness?"

213
00:09:39.307 --> 00:09:40.320
"Yes."

214
00:09:40.320 --> 00:09:42.900
Boom, I'm gonna do the questionnaire,

215
00:09:42.900 --> 00:09:46.590
and see if they meet criteria for a sleep study.

216
00:09:46.590 --> 00:09:48.030
If they don't snore,

217
00:09:48.030 --> 00:09:50.490
and they don't have excessive daytime sleepiness,

218
00:09:50.490 --> 00:09:51.840
they would not be screened.

219
00:09:54.120 --> 00:09:56.370
In 2019, the American Academy of Sleep Medicine

220
00:09:56.370 --> 00:09:58.110
updated their recommendations.

221
00:09:58.110 --> 00:10:02.310
They say if you have high clinical suspicion,

222
00:10:02.310 --> 00:10:04.110
a home-based study should be followed

223
00:10:04.110 --> 00:10:07.020
by a full polysomnography,

224
00:10:07.020 --> 00:10:09.000
if you really think they have sleep apnea,

225
00:10:09.000 --> 00:10:11.190
even despite the negative test.

226
00:10:11.190 --> 00:10:13.680
Or you should repeat the polysomnography

227
00:10:13.680 --> 00:10:15.360
under high clinical suspicion.

228
00:10:15.360 --> 00:10:17.940
You might also wanna repeat a study if something changes.

229
00:10:17.940 --> 00:10:21.750
Maybe they're on Ozempic, and they've lost 50 pounds.

230
00:10:21.750 --> 00:10:23.400
We've seen that in clinical practice,

231
00:10:23.400 --> 00:10:25.300
I've had patients lose over 100 pounds

232
00:10:26.160 --> 00:10:28.203
on these GLP-1 agonists.

233
00:10:29.130 --> 00:10:31.890
If they've had an operative intervention,

234
00:10:31.890 --> 00:10:33.270
if they've had improvement

235
00:10:33.270 --> 00:10:35.340
with their oral mandibular advice,

236
00:10:35.340 --> 00:10:38.760
or if you think they might have central sleep apnea.

237
00:10:38.760 --> 00:10:41.700
Your treatment here, you've got a CPAP,

238
00:10:41.700 --> 00:10:44.430
that's Continuous Positive Airway Pressure.

239
00:10:44.430 --> 00:10:45.930
Again, this is a money slide,

240
00:10:45.930 --> 00:10:50.130
so you're gonna use this for mild or moderate,

241
00:10:50.130 --> 00:10:53.040
I'm sorry, moderate or severe sleep apnea,

242
00:10:53.040 --> 00:10:55.980
or mild, if they have comorbidities.

243
00:10:55.980 --> 00:10:59.940
So if they've got other chronic illnesses going on,

244
00:10:59.940 --> 00:11:02.490
mild sleep apnea qualifies for treatment as well,

245
00:11:02.490 --> 00:11:04.830
so that's important to remember.

246
00:11:04.830 --> 00:11:07.260
There's also Bilevel PAP, that's BiPAP,

247
00:11:07.260 --> 00:11:09.683
and auto-titrating CPAPs.

248
00:11:10.710 --> 00:11:13.980
The next best treatment is an oromandibular advice.

249
00:11:13.980 --> 00:11:15.990
How many of us are familiar with these?

250
00:11:15.990 --> 00:11:17.520
This is a dental appliance,

251
00:11:17.520 --> 00:11:19.410
so, they go to the dentist, they get fitted for it,

252
00:11:19.410 --> 00:11:20.610
they wear it at night,

253
00:11:20.610 --> 00:11:23.910
and it basically forces the mandible forward,

254
00:11:23.910 --> 00:11:25.530
creating more space,

255
00:11:25.530 --> 00:11:29.013
and that improves their sleep apnea.

256
00:11:30.090 --> 00:11:31.080
They tend to be expensive,

257
00:11:31.080 --> 00:11:32.850
they tend to run like a couple thousand,

258
00:11:32.850 --> 00:11:34.320
and I don't know that the insurance companies

259
00:11:34.320 --> 00:11:35.670
always cover them,

260
00:11:35.670 --> 00:11:38.730
but that has the next best data.

261
00:11:38.730 --> 00:11:42.060
Weight loss is definitely essential.

262
00:11:42.060 --> 00:11:43.860
You know, obesity is one of the main risk factors

263
00:11:43.860 --> 00:11:45.060
for this illness,

264
00:11:45.060 --> 00:11:46.710
so if you can get a patient to lose weight,

265
00:11:46.710 --> 00:11:49.023
that can definitely improve their sleep apnea.

266
00:11:49.920 --> 00:11:52.320
The last one, surgical therapy,

267
00:11:52.320 --> 00:11:54.210
the uvulopalatopharyngoplasty,

268
00:11:54.210 --> 00:11:56.490
I love that word, just rolls right off the tongue.

269
00:11:56.490 --> 00:11:59.040
UP3, the otolaryngologists call it,

270
00:11:59.040 --> 00:12:01.110
they're basically rotarying in the back of the throat,

271
00:12:01.110 --> 00:12:03.060
so they're taking out all that extra tissue.

272
00:12:03.060 --> 00:12:04.950
Now, anecdotally,

273
00:12:04.950 --> 00:12:08.550
otolaryngology insists that this is effective,

274
00:12:08.550 --> 00:12:11.730
but we just don't have a clinical study to prove it,

275
00:12:11.730 --> 00:12:14.130
so therefore you're probably not gonna see that option

276
00:12:14.130 --> 00:12:15.123
on the boards.

277
00:12:17.760 --> 00:12:20.280
How many of us are familiar with Inspire?

278
00:12:20.280 --> 00:12:22.110
Inspire's the new kid on the block,

279
00:12:22.110 --> 00:12:24.810
this is basically pacemaker technology,

280
00:12:24.810 --> 00:12:27.600
where they surgically implant a wire

281
00:12:27.600 --> 00:12:30.693
that stimulates the hypoglossal nerve when they're sleeping.

282
00:12:31.710 --> 00:12:34.320
Indications are moderate to severe sleep apnea,

283
00:12:34.320 --> 00:12:37.020
they can't tolerate their CPAP,

284
00:12:37.020 --> 00:12:38.280
they have a low BMI,

285
00:12:38.280 --> 00:12:40.260
because it doesn't work as well in obese patients,

286
00:12:40.260 --> 00:12:42.063
and they have to be at least 18.

287
00:12:43.440 --> 00:12:46.713
So, those patients may qualify for the Inspire therapy.

288
00:12:48.360 --> 00:12:51.000
All right, moving on to another topic.

289
00:12:51.000 --> 00:12:56.000
This topic is one where I think I had three questions,

290
00:12:56.250 --> 00:12:59.580
maybe four, on the boards with this next topic,

291
00:12:59.580 --> 00:13:01.260
so this is a heavy hitter.

292
00:13:01.260 --> 00:13:03.840
Always, always, always pops up on the boards.

293
00:13:03.840 --> 00:13:08.840
So, we have a 25-year-old African-American female.

294
00:13:09.180 --> 00:13:11.970
Ding, ding, ding, ding, ding, ding, ding, ding, ding.

295
00:13:11.970 --> 00:13:14.130
This is important, folks.

296
00:13:14.130 --> 00:13:16.380
Who's involved in a motor vehicle accident,

297
00:13:16.380 --> 00:13:20.040
found to have bilateral hilar infiltrates on chest x-ray.

298
00:13:20.040 --> 00:13:21.300
They are asymptomatic,

299
00:13:21.300 --> 00:13:25.020
and have no history of environmental exposures.

300
00:13:25.020 --> 00:13:27.150
The remainder of the exam is unremarkable.

301
00:13:27.150 --> 00:13:30.240
Pulmonary function testing, PPD, are negative.

302
00:13:30.240 --> 00:13:35.240
Transbronchial biopsy reveals a noncaseating granuloma.

303
00:13:35.910 --> 00:13:36.780
Which one of the following

304
00:13:36.780 --> 00:13:38.580
would be the most appropriate treatment in this case?

305
00:13:38.580 --> 00:13:40.560
So you need to know what the diagnosis is,

306
00:13:40.560 --> 00:13:41.400
now what's the treatment?

307
00:13:41.400 --> 00:13:43.203
A., observation?

308
00:13:44.370 --> 00:13:48.120
B., inhaled long-acting beta2-agonist?

309
00:13:48.120 --> 00:13:50.610
C., inhaled corticosteroid?

310
00:13:50.610 --> 00:13:54.420
Or D., systemic corticosteroids?

311
00:13:54.420 --> 00:13:58.473
What should we do in this patient?

312
00:13:59.970 --> 00:14:01.590
Now, remember, they're asymptomatic,

313
00:14:01.590 --> 00:14:03.340
and this was an incidental finding.

314
00:14:10.050 --> 00:14:12.210
Excellent, good, observation.

315
00:14:12.210 --> 00:14:15.090
Systemic corticosteroids would be the option

316
00:14:15.090 --> 00:14:19.113
if she were symptomatic with her sarcoidosis.

317
00:14:20.250 --> 00:14:22.140
All right, so sarcoid,

318
00:14:22.140 --> 00:14:23.670
systemic granulomatous disease,

319
00:14:23.670 --> 00:14:24.900
we don't really know what causes it,

320
00:14:24.900 --> 00:14:26.940
we think it could be a reaction to some infection,

321
00:14:26.940 --> 00:14:28.590
we're not sure.

322
00:14:28.590 --> 00:14:30.960
There's a slight African-American and younger predominance,

323
00:14:30.960 --> 00:14:32.460
that's why I mentioned the patient

324
00:14:32.460 --> 00:14:34.170
was younger and African-American,

325
00:14:34.170 --> 00:14:36.180
so that will sometimes clue you in.

326
00:14:36.180 --> 00:14:39.870
Patients often present with bilateral hilar adenopathy,

327
00:14:39.870 --> 00:14:42.063
interstitial pulmonary infiltrates,

328
00:14:43.050 --> 00:14:45.300
eye problems, and skin problems.

329
00:14:45.300 --> 00:14:46.653
Pay attention to that.

330
00:14:48.210 --> 00:14:49.800
So you'll see, obviously,

331
00:14:49.800 --> 00:14:51.930
your clinical and radiographic findings,

332
00:14:51.930 --> 00:14:55.860
and then noncaseating epitheloid granulomas.

333
00:14:55.860 --> 00:14:59.520
That is the gold standard

334
00:14:59.520 --> 00:15:02.223
by which you would diagnose sarcoidosis.

335
00:15:04.110 --> 00:15:06.330
Okay, differential?

336
00:15:06.330 --> 00:15:09.300
Well, any atypical pneumonias might present this way,

337
00:15:09.300 --> 00:15:11.430
with, you know, interstitial infiltrates

338
00:15:11.430 --> 00:15:12.750
and hilar adenopathy.

339
00:15:12.750 --> 00:15:13.770
TB.

340
00:15:13.770 --> 00:15:17.100
Lymphoma especially would be on your differential,

341
00:15:17.100 --> 00:15:19.920
that's why you're gonna do a biopsy.

342
00:15:19.920 --> 00:15:21.510
Most patients are asymptomatic,

343
00:15:21.510 --> 00:15:23.910
this can be found on routine radiographs.

344
00:15:23.910 --> 00:15:26.793
About a third have some non-specific symptoms.

345
00:15:27.720 --> 00:15:31.560
If they have sarcoid disease,

346
00:15:31.560 --> 00:15:33.450
90% of them are gonna have lung symptoms,

347
00:15:33.450 --> 00:15:35.550
with cough, dyspnea, and chest discomfort.

348
00:15:36.840 --> 00:15:38.040
In those cases,

349
00:15:38.040 --> 00:15:41.253
you're going to treat with systemic corticosteroids.

350
00:15:44.520 --> 00:15:49.050
In severe cases, you may treat them with cytotoxic agents,

351
00:15:49.050 --> 00:15:52.290
anti-malarials, all sorts of issues,

352
00:15:52.290 --> 00:15:56.490
all the way up to lung and cardiac transplantation.

353
00:15:56.490 --> 00:15:59.370
Now, this next bullet point is important.

354
00:15:59.370 --> 00:16:01.020
I think this is more likely the type of question

355
00:16:01.020 --> 00:16:02.700
you might see on the boards.

356
00:16:02.700 --> 00:16:04.290
You've got a patient with sarcoid,

357
00:16:04.290 --> 00:16:07.533
you know, she might be co-managed by specialties.

358
00:16:09.870 --> 00:16:13.680
She's on prednisone, 20 milligrams a day,

359
00:16:13.680 --> 00:16:15.270
to control her sarcoid.

360
00:16:15.270 --> 00:16:18.780
One thing you have to screen for would be osteoporosis,

361
00:16:18.780 --> 00:16:20.460
because that's one of the sequelae

362
00:16:20.460 --> 00:16:22.230
of long-term corticosteroid use.

363
00:16:22.230 --> 00:16:25.027
Those are the type of questions you're more likely to see

364
00:16:25.027 --> 00:16:26.493
on the boards.

365
00:16:28.530 --> 00:16:31.470
Now, there's several stages of sarcoid.

366
00:16:31.470 --> 00:16:34.530
Stage zero is pretty much normal,

367
00:16:34.530 --> 00:16:36.150
even though they actually have the disease,

368
00:16:36.150 --> 00:16:37.500
the chest x-ray looks fine.

369
00:16:37.500 --> 00:16:41.520
Stage one, you see the bilateral hilar lymph adenopathy.

370
00:16:41.520 --> 00:16:45.930
Stage two, you have that, plus parenchymal infiltrates.

371
00:16:45.930 --> 00:16:48.270
If that progresses to stage three,

372
00:16:48.270 --> 00:16:51.090
they keep the infiltrates, but lose the lymph adenopathy.

373
00:16:51.090 --> 00:16:55.410
And then stage four is fibrotic lung disease.

374
00:16:55.410 --> 00:16:58.050
The worse it is, the lower the likelihood

375
00:16:58.050 --> 00:17:00.570
that they're gonna have spontaneous remission.

376
00:17:00.570 --> 00:17:02.070
So, here's some radiographs.

377
00:17:02.070 --> 00:17:03.300
On the left, Stage I,

378
00:17:03.300 --> 00:17:06.630
you see the hilar lymphadenopathy.

379
00:17:06.630 --> 00:17:09.450
We skip Stage II, into Stage III,

380
00:17:09.450 --> 00:17:10.283
and that's where we get

381
00:17:10.283 --> 00:17:12.480
the bilateral parenchymal infiltrates.

382
00:17:12.480 --> 00:17:14.610
And then if that progresses to Stage IV,

383
00:17:14.610 --> 00:17:18.093
you get pulmonary fibrosis, and that would be incurable.

384
00:17:21.630 --> 00:17:24.510
Early patients may have no symptoms,

385
00:17:24.510 --> 00:17:27.990
later patients, obviously, all sort of things can happen.

386
00:17:27.990 --> 00:17:29.100
This last one I included

387
00:17:29.100 --> 00:17:32.130
because it's popped up on the board every once in a while,

388
00:17:32.130 --> 00:17:33.840
spontaneous remission often occurs

389
00:17:33.840 --> 00:17:36.390
in patients with Lofgren's syndrome,

390
00:17:36.390 --> 00:17:39.000
and that consists of bilateral hilar lymphadenopathy,

391
00:17:39.000 --> 00:17:41.730
ankle arthritis, erythema nodosum,

392
00:17:41.730 --> 00:17:44.670
you know what that looks like from your cocci patient,

393
00:17:44.670 --> 00:17:46.710
fever, myalgia, and weight loss.

394
00:17:46.710 --> 00:17:48.960
So, that's Lofgren's syndrome,

395
00:17:48.960 --> 00:17:52.440
and that's, every now and again, popped up on the boards.

396
00:17:52.440 --> 00:17:53.790
Now, this is important,

397
00:17:53.790 --> 00:17:55.110
extra pulmonary sites.

398
00:17:55.110 --> 00:17:58.020
Granted this is largely a pulmonary disease, right?

399
00:17:58.020 --> 00:18:00.330
But it will next affect the lymph systems.

400
00:18:00.330 --> 00:18:02.760
So, you can see the liver or spleen involvement.

401
00:18:02.760 --> 00:18:06.390
After lungs and lymph, it's ocular.

402
00:18:06.390 --> 00:18:09.900
So, the ocular problem that you will see

403
00:18:09.900 --> 00:18:13.680
is acute anterior uveitis.

404
00:18:13.680 --> 00:18:16.350
I was asked this question on the boards,

405
00:18:16.350 --> 00:18:18.690
and I was also asked the follow-up question,

406
00:18:18.690 --> 00:18:20.250
that it may be asymptomatic,

407
00:18:20.250 --> 00:18:22.470
so a yearly eye exam is now recommended

408
00:18:22.470 --> 00:18:24.813
for your patients with active sarcoid.

409
00:18:26.010 --> 00:18:30.210
Now, if you pay attention to the Q&amp;A session's answers,

410
00:18:30.210 --> 00:18:33.300
I've been giving you supplemental slides,

411
00:18:33.300 --> 00:18:35.010
I'm gonna give you one on this one,

412
00:18:35.010 --> 00:18:39.990
and I'm gonna give you a full ophthalmology set as well.

413
00:18:39.990 --> 00:18:41.370
So, that might be helpful for you,

414
00:18:41.370 --> 00:18:43.563
so tune into that.

415
00:18:45.270 --> 00:18:47.670
And then last would be skin involvement.

416
00:18:47.670 --> 00:18:49.890
Neurosarcoid and cardiac granulomas

417
00:18:49.890 --> 00:18:51.993
are actually fairly rare with sarcoid.

418
00:18:53.100 --> 00:18:53.970
You don't have to treat,

419
00:18:53.970 --> 00:18:56.340
if you do, it's gonna be oral steroids,

420
00:18:56.340 --> 00:18:58.473
usually at a fairly high dose.

421
00:19:00.480 --> 00:19:04.170
Cytotoxic agents, of course, in the worst cases,

422
00:19:04.170 --> 00:19:06.630
the middle bullet point I like,

423
00:19:06.630 --> 00:19:08.250
calcitonin and bisphosphonates

424
00:19:08.250 --> 00:19:10.500
may be useful in preventing osteoporosis.

425
00:19:10.500 --> 00:19:11.333
So that's, again,

426
00:19:11.333 --> 00:19:13.040
the type of question that you could see.

427
00:19:14.340 --> 00:19:15.630
Also, rarely on the boards,

428
00:19:15.630 --> 00:19:16.680
but I have seen it,

429
00:19:16.680 --> 00:19:19.110
some follow ACE levels in the blood

430
00:19:19.110 --> 00:19:20.660
to follow the disease activity.

431
00:19:22.110 --> 00:19:24.360
And that is sarcoid.

432
00:19:24.360 --> 00:19:26.550
I promise you that there will be questions

433
00:19:26.550 --> 00:19:28.413
about sarcoidosis on the exam,

434
00:19:29.370 --> 00:19:30.723
so please know those.

435
00:19:31.770 --> 00:19:35.490
Moving on to granulomatosis with polyangiitis.

436
00:19:35.490 --> 00:19:38.370
We used to call this Wegener's Granulomatosis.

437
00:19:38.370 --> 00:19:41.340
This is a necrotizing granulomatous vasculitis

438
00:19:41.340 --> 00:19:44.970
that affects the respiratory tract and the kidneys,

439
00:19:44.970 --> 00:19:47.490
with focal segmental glomerulonephritis.

440
00:19:47.490 --> 00:19:49.620
We don't know what causes it.

441
00:19:49.620 --> 00:19:50.453
Unlike sarcoid,

442
00:19:50.453 --> 00:19:53.433
this tends to occur more in younger white males.

443
00:19:54.420 --> 00:19:57.063
The symptoms can be respiratory and urine.

444
00:19:58.140 --> 00:20:00.180
You can follow ANCA levels,

445
00:20:00.180 --> 00:20:02.730
and corticosteroids are of course the mainstay

446
00:20:02.730 --> 00:20:04.260
of treatment here.

447
00:20:04.260 --> 00:20:05.093
Clearly, you know,

448
00:20:05.093 --> 00:20:07.080
these patients, you're gonna be consulting pulmonology,

449
00:20:07.080 --> 00:20:09.390
you're gonna be consulting infectious disease,

450
00:20:09.390 --> 00:20:11.520
you're gonna be consulting nephrology.

451
00:20:11.520 --> 00:20:12.870
That's one of the things that drives me crazy

452
00:20:12.870 --> 00:20:14.040
about the boards,

453
00:20:14.040 --> 00:20:17.850
is that a lot of times they expect us to know

454
00:20:17.850 --> 00:20:18.930
these high-end treatments,

455
00:20:18.930 --> 00:20:21.540
when, really, in practical terms,

456
00:20:21.540 --> 00:20:25.413
the answer is, refer to specialty, right?

457
00:20:26.700 --> 00:20:28.890
All right, next question.

458
00:20:28.890 --> 00:20:32.370
You see a previously healthy 60-year-old non-smoker

459
00:20:32.370 --> 00:20:35.250
who consults you for progressive dyspnea and cough.

460
00:20:35.250 --> 00:20:36.180
Vitals are stable,

461
00:20:36.180 --> 00:20:38.550
physical exam is significant for nail clubbing,

462
00:20:38.550 --> 00:20:42.000
decreased breath sounds with bilateral coarse crackles.

463
00:20:42.000 --> 00:20:43.770
You perform office spirometry.

464
00:20:43.770 --> 00:20:45.185
Good for you.

465
00:20:45.185 --> 00:20:47.370
How many do office spirometry?

466
00:20:47.370 --> 00:20:49.590
It's very easy to do. It's simple.

467
00:20:49.590 --> 00:20:51.000
Good.

468
00:20:51.000 --> 00:20:53.340
Which one of the following results on your spirometry

469
00:20:53.340 --> 00:20:56.790
are consistent with a diagnosis of restrictive lung disease?

470
00:20:56.790 --> 00:20:59.010
We already went over obstructive lung diseases,

471
00:20:59.010 --> 00:21:01.140
now let's talk about restrictive.

472
00:21:01.140 --> 00:21:06.000
A., a decreased FVC and TLC with a decreased FEV1 ratio?

473
00:21:06.000 --> 00:21:09.600
B., same decreased FVC and TLC,

474
00:21:09.600 --> 00:21:11.493
but an increase in the FEV1?

475
00:21:12.870 --> 00:21:16.110
C., an increase in the FVC and TLC,

476
00:21:16.110 --> 00:21:18.390
with a decrease in the FEV1?

477
00:21:18.390 --> 00:21:22.653
And D., a increase in the FVC and TLC,

478
00:21:23.700 --> 00:21:25.380
with an increase in the FEV1?

479
00:21:25.380 --> 00:21:27.600
Unfortunately, this isn't one you can sleuth out,

480
00:21:27.600 --> 00:21:30.210
'cause none of 'em have enough in common

481
00:21:30.210 --> 00:21:33.780
that you can make a cross-section.

482
00:21:33.780 --> 00:21:35.100
But if you think about it,

483
00:21:35.100 --> 00:21:38.490
like we talked about what obstructive lung diseases do

484
00:21:38.490 --> 00:21:41.793
with FEV1, right?

485
00:21:43.140 --> 00:21:46.170
And if you think about restrictive lung disease,

486
00:21:46.170 --> 00:21:47.370
everything is restricted,

487
00:21:47.370 --> 00:21:50.760
you don't have the ability to breathe

488
00:21:50.760 --> 00:21:52.380
because of the restrictive process,

489
00:21:52.380 --> 00:21:55.380
which could be intrathoracic or extrathoracic, by the way.

490
00:21:55.380 --> 00:21:58.473
So, you can kind of sleuth this one out just by knowing it.

491
00:22:03.390 --> 00:22:04.980
So, you're going to get both,

492
00:22:04.980 --> 00:22:08.490
both decreased FVC and total lung capacity

493
00:22:08.490 --> 00:22:09.723
are gonna be decreased,

494
00:22:10.800 --> 00:22:15.800
and your FEV1 would be normal, or increased,

495
00:22:16.110 --> 00:22:18.660
as opposed to obstructive,

496
00:22:18.660 --> 00:22:21.900
when it's decreased below 70%, right?

497
00:22:21.900 --> 00:22:23.040
So, that's the right answer.

498
00:22:23.040 --> 00:22:23.873
Good job.

499
00:22:25.050 --> 00:22:28.650
So, this is a heterogeneous set of pulmonary disorders,

500
00:22:28.650 --> 00:22:30.540
all of them cause restrictive patterns.

501
00:22:30.540 --> 00:22:32.370
You have reduced distensibility of the lungs,

502
00:22:32.370 --> 00:22:34.020
that compromises expansion,

503
00:22:34.020 --> 00:22:36.210
so you get reduced lung volumes,

504
00:22:36.210 --> 00:22:39.150
especially your total lung capacity.

505
00:22:39.150 --> 00:22:42.273
So that differentiates them from our obstructive diseases.

506
00:22:43.830 --> 00:22:45.240
This could be, again, like I said,

507
00:22:45.240 --> 00:22:46.800
intrinsic or extrinsic.

508
00:22:46.800 --> 00:22:49.470
The intrinsic causes are, you know,

509
00:22:49.470 --> 00:22:51.120
distal lung parenchymal damage

510
00:22:51.120 --> 00:22:55.263
from all sorts of different disease processes.

511
00:22:57.030 --> 00:23:01.620
Or you could get extrinsic musculoskeletal

512
00:23:01.620 --> 00:23:03.330
neuromuscular disorders,

513
00:23:03.330 --> 00:23:04.440
extreme obesity,

514
00:23:04.440 --> 00:23:07.020
where you just don't have the wall movements.

515
00:23:07.020 --> 00:23:07.853
So, let's take a look.

516
00:23:07.853 --> 00:23:09.780
Your intrinsic causes,

517
00:23:09.780 --> 00:23:11.940
idiopathic pulmonary fibrosis,

518
00:23:11.940 --> 00:23:13.650
sarcoid,

519
00:23:13.650 --> 00:23:15.300
interstitial pneumonias,

520
00:23:15.300 --> 00:23:17.490
organic and inorganic dust exposures,

521
00:23:17.490 --> 00:23:21.480
those are those environmental, occupational lung diseases.

522
00:23:21.480 --> 00:23:23.100
Systemic sclerosis,

523
00:23:23.100 --> 00:23:24.270
pulmonary vasculitis,

524
00:23:24.270 --> 00:23:25.890
radiation therapy,

525
00:23:25.890 --> 00:23:27.750
Langerhans Cell Histiocytosis,

526
00:23:27.750 --> 00:23:30.270
that's formerly called Histiocytosis X.

527
00:23:30.270 --> 00:23:32.463
And then some medications, long-term,

528
00:23:33.510 --> 00:23:38.510
can cause restrictive lung diseases and pulmonary fibrosis.

529
00:23:40.890 --> 00:23:42.660
Your extrinsic causes,

530
00:23:42.660 --> 00:23:46.800
decreased neuromuscular tone from muscular dystrophy,

531
00:23:46.800 --> 00:23:50.280
ALS, polio, et cetera.

532
00:23:50.280 --> 00:23:51.780
Deformations of the rib cage,

533
00:23:51.780 --> 00:23:53.040
where you just can't,

534
00:23:53.040 --> 00:23:54.960
you know, you don't have the capacity.

535
00:23:54.960 --> 00:23:56.943
Decreased space, like pleural effusions,

536
00:23:56.943 --> 00:23:59.160
pneumothorax, ascites, and obesity.

537
00:23:59.160 --> 00:24:01.710
Obesity is on the rise in this country.

538
00:24:01.710 --> 00:24:04.500
You can get obesity hypoventilation syndrome,

539
00:24:04.500 --> 00:24:06.510
formerly called Pickwickian syndrome,

540
00:24:06.510 --> 00:24:09.480
where the weight of the fat is so great

541
00:24:09.480 --> 00:24:11.640
that the patient has a hard time expanding their chest

542
00:24:11.640 --> 00:24:12.473
and breathing.

543
00:24:15.000 --> 00:24:16.620
Okay, so what you're gonna see here,

544
00:24:16.620 --> 00:24:19.530
a decreased TLC and forced vital capacity,

545
00:24:19.530 --> 00:24:23.670
A TLC less than 80% is pathognomonic

546
00:24:23.670 --> 00:24:26.520
for restrictive diseases.

547
00:24:26.520 --> 00:24:28.320
And then we rank them as mild, moderate,

548
00:24:28.320 --> 00:24:29.913
moderately severe, or severe.

549
00:24:31.710 --> 00:24:33.810
This slide, I would try to commit to memory,

550
00:24:33.810 --> 00:24:35.700
it's fairly straightforward,

551
00:24:35.700 --> 00:24:37.920
but these are the spirometric findings that you'll see.

552
00:24:37.920 --> 00:24:39.000
With restrictive patterns,

553
00:24:39.000 --> 00:24:42.060
you're gonna see a decreased FVC and TLC,

554
00:24:42.060 --> 00:24:45.123
with a normal to high FEV1.

555
00:24:46.110 --> 00:24:48.120
With obstructive patterns,

556
00:24:48.120 --> 00:24:51.060
we have a normal FVC and TLC,

557
00:24:51.060 --> 00:24:52.787
but with a decreased FEV1,

558
00:24:52.787 --> 00:24:55.140
'cause it's that breathing through the straw thing

559
00:24:55.140 --> 00:24:56.910
with the obstruction, right?

560
00:24:56.910 --> 00:25:00.123
So, it makes sense when you think about them.

561
00:25:02.250 --> 00:25:03.330
The history and physical here,

562
00:25:03.330 --> 00:25:05.520
obviously the symptoms,

563
00:25:05.520 --> 00:25:07.860
you're gonna have an insidious progression of dyspnea,

564
00:25:07.860 --> 00:25:09.480
it gets worse over time.

565
00:25:09.480 --> 00:25:12.480
And classically, you'll see the three C's,

566
00:25:12.480 --> 00:25:17.340
cough, clubbing of the nails, and crackles on auscultation.

567
00:25:17.340 --> 00:25:19.410
How many of us in clinical practice

568
00:25:19.410 --> 00:25:21.630
have actually seen clubbing?

569
00:25:21.630 --> 00:25:23.330
A good number of you. That's good.

570
00:25:24.480 --> 00:25:25.590
So, let's talk about that.

571
00:25:25.590 --> 00:25:27.720
Here's a picture of nail clubbing.

572
00:25:27.720 --> 00:25:32.130
You see the distal digits look like a club,

573
00:25:32.130 --> 00:25:34.233
so that's literally a descriptive term.

574
00:25:36.750 --> 00:25:39.690
One way you can diagnose it is Schamroth's sign.

575
00:25:39.690 --> 00:25:41.880
So, I want everybody to do this,

576
00:25:41.880 --> 00:25:44.220
take your index fingers, put 'em together,

577
00:25:44.220 --> 00:25:45.300
look at a light source,

578
00:25:45.300 --> 00:25:47.880
and you should see a little diamond in the middle.

579
00:25:47.880 --> 00:25:48.750
That's the gap,

580
00:25:48.750 --> 00:25:53.750
the space between the fingernails.

581
00:25:53.940 --> 00:25:56.790
So you get that divot of about 165 degrees

582
00:25:56.790 --> 00:25:58.980
right there at the union, the lunula,

583
00:25:58.980 --> 00:26:02.373
which is where the nails exit the skin.

584
00:26:03.300 --> 00:26:07.920
If they lose that angle, called the Lovibond angle,

585
00:26:07.920 --> 00:26:11.190
then that obliterates that space,

586
00:26:11.190 --> 00:26:13.170
and you don't have a space.

587
00:26:13.170 --> 00:26:15.510
If anyone does this and doesn't have a space, (laughs)

588
00:26:15.510 --> 00:26:17.049
you better be concerned.

589
00:26:17.049 --> 00:26:19.500
(audience members laughing)

590
00:26:19.500 --> 00:26:22.440
So, that's how you diagnose nail clubbing.

591
00:26:22.440 --> 00:26:24.540
Now, the treatment, it varies.

592
00:26:24.540 --> 00:26:26.250
Immunosuppressive drugs,

593
00:26:26.250 --> 00:26:31.250
you know, it's not easy to treat restrictive lung diseases,

594
00:26:31.380 --> 00:26:32.520
a lot of times it's symptomatic,

595
00:26:32.520 --> 00:26:34.583
and a lot of times they have a poor outcome.

596
00:26:35.610 --> 00:26:38.490
And we are done with pulmonology.

597
00:26:38.490 --> 00:26:41.123
Y'all have done great.
(audience applauding)

598
00:26:41.123 --> 00:26:44.206
(gentle outro music)

